{"title_page": "Worldreader", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n| name              = Worldreader\n| image             = Worldreader Official Logo.jpg\n| image_size        = 220px\n| type              = Non-governmental organization\n| founded_date      = {{start date and age|2010}}\n| tax_id            = \n| registration_id   =\n| founder           = [[David Risher]], Colin McElwee\n| location          = [[San Francisco, California]]<br />[[Barcelona, Spain]]\n[[Accra, Ghana]]<br />[[Nairobi, Kenya]]<br />[[Delhi, India]]\n| coordinates       = \n| origins           = \n| key_people        = \n[[David Risher]], Colin McElwee \n| area_served       = Africa, Asia, South America\n| product           = \n| focus             = With low-cost technology, culturally-relevant digital books, and a network of corporate and nonprofit partners, Worldreader helps millions of children and families in the developing world read throughout their lives.\n| method            = \n| revenue           = \n| endowment         = \n| num_volunteers    = \n| num_employees     = \n| num_members       = \n| subsid            = \n| owner             = \n| non-profit_slogan = \n| former name       = \n| homepage          = http://www.worldreader.org\n| dissolved         = \n}}\n'''Worldreader''' is a [[501(c)(3)]] global [[non-profit organization]] that provides people in the developing world with free access to a library of digital books via e-readers and mobile phones.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qoP9uiVqjoA&feature=player_embedded |title=Video&nbsp;\u2013 Katie Linendoll on BrookB |publisher=CNN.com |date=2012-07-06 |accessdate=2011-01-15}}</ref>\n\nSince 2010, over 13 million people across 47 countries have read from Worldreader's digital library of thousands of e-books.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldreader.org/|title=Worldreader: E-books on Cell Phones and Kindles in Schools|website=Worldreader|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-26}}</ref> Worldreader works with device manufacturers, local and international publishers, government agencies, education officials, and local communities to support readers. \n\nThe organization is headquartered in [[San Francisco, California]] and has offices in [[Ghana]], [[Kenya]], [[Spain]] and the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n==Programs==\n\n=== '''COVID-19 Response: Keep Children Reading''' ===\nIn response to the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] crisis, which impacted over 1.5 billion children and youth due to school closures<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.unesco.org/covid19/educationresponse|title=COVID-19 Educational Disruption and Response|last=https://plus.google.com/+UNESCO|date=2020-03-04|website=UNESCO|language=en|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>, Worldreader launched the [https://www.worldreader.org/keep-children-reading/ Keep Children Reading initiative]. The initiative seeks to support children's education at home by making a library of children's books available on mobile phones with Worldreader's BookSmart app. The library contains books about COVID-19 intended to help children better understand the pandemic<ref>{{Cite news|last=Alter|first=Alexandra|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/14/books/coronavirus-picture-books.html|title=Answering Kids\u2019 Questions About the Coronavirus, in Free Picture Books|date=2020-04-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>. \n\n=== Worldreader\u2019s Pre-Primary Program ===\nWorldreader works with partners whose programs reach families, communities, healthcare workers, and preschools seeking to normalize a culture of reading and storytelling early on in a child\u2019s life. The aim of the program is to help young children develop the skills needed to become successful readers.  \n\nAs part of the program, Worldreader's [https://www.worldreader.org/our-solution/products/booksmart/ BookSmart app] gives families access to a free digital library of books in Hindi, English, Spanish, and Arabic, via their mobile phone. Their work in Delhi, India has so far reached 200,000 families<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comms.worldreader.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/READ2KIDS_digital-1.pdf|title=Leveraging Mobile Technology for Parental Engagement in the Early Years|last=|first=|date=May 2018|website=Worldreader|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> with a children's library on their mobile phones. In Jordan, they have so far reached 50,000 vulnerable families impacted by the refugee crisis<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comms.worldreader.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Tuta-Tuta-report_Eng-2.pdf|title=The Benefits of Digital Reading for Vulnerable Families in Crisis Settings|last=|first=|date=November 2019|website=Worldreader|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. \n\n=== Worldreader\u2019s Primary Grade Reading Program ===\n\nThe nonprofit seeks to improve a child\u2019s digital literacy and reading proficiency by focusing on time spent reading and the five core reading skills: phonemic awareness, phonics, fluency, vocabulary, and comprehension. \n\nAs part of the program, Worldreader partners with schools and libraries to deliver digital books to students and library patrons. The organization provides technical and pedagogical training for local project managers and teachers and e-reader repair training for local businesses. They also manage logistics and support in partnership with local governments, school systems, and related businesses.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shapiro|first1=Jordan|title=Education Technology Makes The Most Impact In The Least Recognized Places|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jordanshapiro/2015/06/27/education-technology-makes-the-most-impact-in-the-least-recognized-places/|accessdate=21 August 2015|publisher=Forbes|date=27 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nFor schools or libraries without access to electricity, the non-profit has a solar product, called BB17, that gives schools and libraries the ability to charge and use e-readers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comms.worldreader.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Solar-1-Pager_2016.pdf?x24959|title=Worldreader Solar Solution|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAs of December 2019, the non-profit has distributed digital books to 485 schools and 253 libraries across 18 sub-Saharan African countries.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.worldreader.org/what-we-do/our-projects/|title=Worldreader: E-Reading Projects in Schools and Libraries|newspaper=Worldreader|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Worldreader\u2019s Youth and Adolescents Program ===\n\nWorldreader\u2019s Youth and Adolescents Program aims to engage young people and raise their awareness about gender and life skills. The program focuses on social-emotional learning and 21st century skills development. \n\nAs part of the program, youth and adolescents can access the Worldreader app. The app provides worldwide access to over 12,700 books, educational resources and health information to people with mobile phones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/08/20/tech/mobile/worldreader-readers-kenya/index.html?hpt=te_t1%22|title=E-readers bring hope to Africa's schools|last1=Linendoll|first1=Katie|website=CNN|publisher=CNN|accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref> The non-profit launched the Worldreader app in April 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gigaom.com/2013/04/09/worldreader-counts-500000-users-of-its-e-reading-app-most-in-india-and-nigeria/|title=Worldreader counts 500,000 users of its e-reading app on feature phones|last1=Owen|first1=Laura|website=Gigaom|publisher=Gigaom|accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref> \n\nAs of December 2019, the Worldreader app had 11.7 million readers worldwide, largely due to its partnership with [[Opera Software]],<ref>[http://the-digital-reader.com/2015/09/02/worldreader-and-opera-brings-books-to-5-million-readers-in-africa-via-mobile-phones/ Worldreader and Opera Bring Books to 5 Million Readers in Africa via Mobile Phones] Digital Reader. 2 September 2015</ref> which promotes the mobile app on the [[Opera Mini]] browser in 34 African countries.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Crawshaw|first1=Jo|url=http://blogs.opera.com/news/2015/05/worldreader-microsoft-math-opera-mini/|title=Get free books from Worldreader and Microsoft Math on Opera Mini|date=15 May 2015|accessdate=22 July 2015|publisher=Opera}}</ref> The app is also available on Microsoft [[Windows Store]], in Mozilla's [[Firefox Marketplace]] and Google's [[Play Store]].\n\n==Governance==\n\nWorldreader is organized as a [[501c3]] charitable organization in the United States, and has received a Guidestar Transparency Seal. Its U.S. Board of Directors<ref name=\"US Board Members\">{{cite web|title=US Board Members|url=http://www.worldreader.org/about-us/board-members/|publisher=Worldreader|accessdate=11 February 2013}}</ref> consists of: David Risher (president), Peter Spiro (chair), Charles Brighton, Chris Capossela, Elizabeth Dollar, Kate James, Elizabeth Khuri Chandler, Colin McElwee, Lisa Nitze, Kartik Raghavan, Dana Reid, and Alison Rich. In Spain, the organization operates as a registered non-profit foundation validated by the Ministry of Education with the registration number 1361.\n \nCo-founders [[David Risher]] and Colin McElwee lead the organization from [[San Francisco, California]] and [[Barcelona, Spain]]. A mix of private social investors, corporate sponsors, and government agencies including [[USAID]] funds the organization.<ref name=\"Brookings Institution\">{{cite web|url=http://www.brookings.edu/papers/2011/0128_literacy_vandergaag.aspx|title=First Step to Literacy: Getting Books in the Hands of Children|publisher=Brookings Institution |date= |accessdate=2011-01-28}}</ref>\n\n== Studies ==\nThe organization conducts [[monitoring and evaluation]] for impact assessment, develops reading focused out-of-classroom activities and teacher workshops by working with communities and partner organizations. Its research shows that students in the e-reader programs improved 94% in mother tongue oral reading fluency after 5 months, and girls in the e-reader programs improved twice as fast in oral reading fluency as girls in neighboring schools, closing an existing gender gap.<ref>{{cite web|title=iREAD 2 Midterm Study Results: All Children Reading in Ghana 2013|url=http://cdn.worldreader.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Midterm-Results-Study.pdf|website=Worldreader|publisher=Worldreader|accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref> The Worldreader iREAD 2 project was funded by an All Children Reading grant from [[USAID]], [[World Vision]] and [[AusAid]], aimed to improve early grade reading skills for students in Ghana. The project's final report,<ref>{{cite web|title=iREAD Study 2012-2014|url=http://cdn.worldreader.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/iREAD-final_web2.pdf|website=Worldreader|publisher=Worldreader|accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>  in November 2014,  showed significant improvements in oral reading fluency, reading comprehension gains, significant impact among low-performing students and development of positive reading habits. Worldreader has shown that reading from the Worldreader Open Library is particularly popular with women, who spend on average 207 minutes reading per month, compared to 32 minutes for men.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reading in the Mobile Era: A UNESCO study of mobile reading in developing countries|url=http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0022/002274/227436E.pdf|publisher=UNESCO}}</ref>\n\nProject LEAP, a pilot program implemented by Worldreader in partnership with eight public and community libraries in western Kenya, and funded by the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation, examined the use of e-readers in selected libraries to determine how e-readers affect library patronage, communities, staff, policies and procedures. The primary impacts  included a threefold increase in library visits, from 10,442 to 29,023 patrons per month, 254 library-initiated community events and 84% of patrons reported increased reading.<ref name=\"Project LEAP Final Report 2015\">{{cite web|title=Project LEAP Final Report 2015|url=http://cdn.worldreader.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/PROJECT_LEAP.pdf|website=Worldreader|publisher=Worldreader|accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n2019: Reimagine Education Awards: Silver Award Winner in the Learning Assessment category for Using Digital Reading Data to Measure and Facilitate Literacy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reimagine-education.com/regional-2020-award-winners-2/|title=Learning Assessment Award|last=|first=|date=|website=Reimagine Education|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> \n\n2019: Reimagine Education Awards: Gold Award Winner in the Europe Award category for Using Digital Reading Data to Measure and Facilitate Literacy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reimagine-education.com/regional-2020-award-winners-2/|title=Regional 2020 Award Winners|website=Reimagine Education|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\n2017: National Technology Awards: Innovation of the Year Winner for Worldreader<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nationaltechnologyawards.co.uk/shortlist17.php|title=National Technology Awards|website=nationaltechnologyawards.co.uk|access-date=2018-07-11}}</ref>\n\n2017: London Book Fair's Charity of the Year<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.londonbookfair.co.uk/Whats-On/Charity-of-The-Year/|title=Charity of the Year - The London Book Fair|date=2015-09-15|website=www.londonbookfair.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-07-11}}</ref>\n\n2017: mBillionth Award: Learning and Education Winner for the Read to Kids pilot program with Pearson India<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comms.worldreader.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/Read-to-Kids-mBillionth-Award-Press-Release-1-1.pdf?x80235|title=Worldreader and Pearson Win mBillionth Award for Read to Kids Program|last=Worldreader|first=|date=11 July 2018|website=worldreader.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n2017: DIGIXX Digital Marketing Excellence in the Charity and NGO category Gold Winners for Read to Kids India<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adgully.com/digixx-awards-2017/categories.php|title=DIGIXX Awards 2017 - Categories|website=www.adgully.com|access-date=2018-07-11}}</ref>\n\n2016: Schwab Foundation: 2016 Schwab Foundation Social Entrepreneurs of the Year, David Risher and Colin McElwee for Worldreader <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://widgets.weforum.org/social-entrepreneurs-2016/|title=Social Entrepreneurs of the Year 2016 - Schwab Foundation|website=widgets.weforum.org|language=en|access-date=2017-11-06}}</ref>\n\n2015: The GSMA Global Mobile Award: Best Mobile Innovation for Education, Worldreader & Opera for the Worldreader app <ref name=\"Best Mobile Innovation for Education 2015\">{{cite web|title=Best Mobile Innovation for Education 2015|url=https://www.globalmobileawards.com/why-enter-the-awards/best-mobile-innovation-for-education-worldreader-opera-for-worldreader-mobile/}}</ref>\n\n2015: The Meffy Awards: The Innovation Award for Mobile-First Market, Worldreader for the Worldreader app <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mobileecosystemforum.com/2016/09/07/meffys-2015-winners-12-months-on-worldreader/|title=Meffys 2015 winners 12 months on: Worldreader - Blog - MEF|date=2016-09-07|work=MEF|access-date=2017-11-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n2015: The Meffy Awards: The Market Award for Social Responsibility, Worldreader for the Worldreader app <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mobileecosystemforum.com/2016/09/07/meffys-2015-winners-12-months-on-worldreader/|title=Meffys 2015 winners 12 months on: Worldreader - Blog - MEF|date=2016-09-07|work=MEF|access-date=2017-11-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Dedicated e-book devices]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in Seattle]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2009]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n| name              = Worldreader\n| image             